  "detailedRequirements": "<p>This challenge is part of Project SERENITY: a refresh of the topcoder challenge lifecycle. There are many challenges before it and will be many after it but you should be able to clone this repo: https://github.com/topcoderinc/serenity-core, grok the README and be up to speed in a few minutes. &nbsp; This project pulls heavily from the MEAN.io stack but with PostgreSQL support.</p>\n\n<p>This should be a pretty fun challenge. &nbsp; As developers we love Markdown, it is a simple and easy to learn syntax for most of the basic formatting we need, It also avoids some of the inherent problems that pasting into a rich text editor introduces. &nbsp;For this challenge we would like to play with and explore some options for using Markdown in Angular.</p>\n\n<p>For simplicity we will use the default articles package (Mongo) but keep in mind the end state will be to use this on the challenge editor which is stored in postgres. &nbsp; There is a really simple angular-markdown-directive https://github.com/btford/angular-markdown-directive by Brian Ford. &nbsp;Very simple to use just encapsulate your directive in his directive. &nbsp; Also there is an awesome markdown preview for atom: https://github.com/atom/markdown-preview that allows users to type markdown and see it rendered in a preview window. &nbsp; It seems like you could do this pretty easily with Brian Ford&rsquo;s package too.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Requirements:</strong><br />\n1. &nbsp;For this challenge choose a markdown, anything is fair game.<br />\n2. Modify the articles package (re-enable it in the menu bar) and give the user an options to write the article in markdown or plain text. &nbsp;The simplest way to do this is provide a checkbox that updates a boolean field in the database to signify if the payload is in markdown or not and render it appropriately in the view. The problem with this approach is when we move to postgres we have to add new isMarkdown fields for every field have. &nbsp;Maybe that is the best approach and I am all ears. &nbsp; However I think we should be able to but a tag in the payload that determines if indeed markdown is used. &nbsp; My idea is that a radio button be placed above any text box that says [] markdown [] html, and if the user selects markdown a class is added to the payload to tell the view weather to render it in markdown or not.<br />\n3. You may take two approaches: a.) just like github: add a preview tab that will render markdown and the user can switch back and form between the two tabs. Or b.) when the user selects markdown they get a preview window. &nbsp; Ghost.org (next generation blogger) does it this way. &nbsp; However this one might be tough to deal with screen real estate since we have multiple places on the same page that we would like to use it. &nbsp;So another option might be a.) tabs + a modal that opens in near full screen with an editor pane and preview pane.&nbsp;</p>\n",
